Amid rising crimes in tricycles (Keke NAPEP) in Borno, the state government has begun the biometric data capturing of operators and owners, to flush out criminal elements in the system. The state’s commissioner of transport, Abubakar Tijani, disclosed this on Saturday in Maiduguri during a ministerial conference to mark the one year anniversary of Pro. Babagana Umara Zulum. The commissioner added that the state government has also purchased 50 buses to boost the capacity of Borno Express Transport Corporation, to enhance transportation in the state. He said: “The framework for the sanitization of the “Keke Napep” tricycle riders, flushing out of the criminal elements within the system and the creating of measures for our entire traffic order is underway. To actualise this, the biometric data capture of all tricycle operators and owners is presently taking place at four different locations.” The commissioner, however, decried loss of revenue to the inter-state travel ban as a result of COVID-19 pandemic, and noted that the ban did not only affect the Borno Express Company, the state’s transport firm, but the entire transport corporations operating in the state. “On the basis of this, we had a meeting in our forum as commissioners of transport, and intimated the Federal Ministry of Transport to intervene by providing palliative, to bring succour to the transport corporations who now cannot pay salaries of their staff,” Hon Tijani said.